## 14k vs. 18k Yellow Gold for a Pear Diamond Ring

The 14k versus 18k decision for a yellow gold pear ring comes down to durability, color richness, and cost.

**14k yellow gold (58.3% gold):** The harder alloy mix makes 14k more durable than 18k. For a pear diamond ring specifically, this matters at the V-prong — the tip prong on a pear diamond takes directional stress every time the ring contacts a surface. A 14k V-prong maintains its grip and shape better over 20–30 years of daily wear than an 18k prong in the same position. 14k is also 15–25% cheaper than 18k for an equivalent setting.

**18k yellow gold (75% gold):** The higher gold content creates a richer, deeper yellow tone that is visible in person. 18k is the European standard for fine jewelry and is common in luxury and bespoke settings. It is marginally softer — prongs wear down slightly faster under the same conditions as 14k, though this difference is not significant with annual professional maintenance.

**The ruling for pear diamonds:** 14k is the practical choice. The V-prong protection is the most mechanically stressed point on any pear diamond ring, and 14k holds it better. The visual color difference between 14k and 18k is subtle — most people cannot distinguish them at arm's length. Invest the 14k price saving in the center stone. The Warm Metal Dividend applies equally to both karatages.

