## Yellow Gold vs. Rose Gold vs. White Gold for a Pear Diamond Ring

Yellow gold is not the correct choice for every pear diamond buyer. The comparison below maps each metal to its ideal use case.

| Factor | Yellow Gold | Rose Gold | White Gold |
|--------|-------------|-----------|------------|
| Warm Metal Dividend | Full — 1–2 grades saved | Moderate — 1 grade saved | None |
| Best diamond color | H–I | H–J | D–H |
| Vintage character | Strong (Victorian/Edwardian) | Moderate (Art Nouveau/romantic) | Minimal |
| Maintenance | None — color is permanent | None — color is permanent | Rhodium replating every 1–3 years |
| Best for fancy color | Yellow, champagne diamonds | Pink, brown diamonds | Blue, green diamonds |
| Style personality | Bold, warm, traditional | Soft, romantic, feminine | Clean, modern, neutral |

**Choose yellow gold** if you want the maximum Warm Metal Dividend, a genuine vintage aesthetic, or you are setting a yellow or champagne fancy color pear diamond.

**Choose rose gold** if you prefer a softer tone, your stone is H–J color, or you are setting a pink or brown fancy color pear. Full metal comparison in the **[pear shaped diamond ring guide](/pear-shaped-diamond-ring)**.

**Choose white gold** if your stone is D–G color and you want the colorless quality to read clean and cold, or your personal style is minimal and modern.

